{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"618a80c4-5a1c-4bae-868f-b5bc0ea729fc","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --collect-coverage \\\n  --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--collect-coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**Prerequisites** — add these NuGet packages to your test project:\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump`\n\nAnd set `<UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>true</UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>` in your test `.csproj` so `dotnet test` delegates to the MTP runner. Everything after `--` is passed as MTP-native arguments.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"52ff1672-04f3-481c-9c50-5c738ce2d56f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences with Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n- `--filter` → `--filter` (same)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` \n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--collect-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage, or you use a different mechanism\n\n\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n- `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nOn .NET 8, `dotnet test` still works as the entry point, but the arguments map differently since the test host processes them differently. With .NET 9+, `dotnet test` can forward arguments directly to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, but on .NET 8 you might need to invoke the test executable directly or use `dotnet run` depending on your setup.\n\nActually, I need to clarify the .NET 8 situation. If you're using Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test` defaults to the VSTest bridge rather than the native runner. To actually use Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, you'd typically build the test project and run the executable directly, or use `dotnet run` with the MTP arguments. Starting with .NET 9, `dotnet test` natively supports Microsoft.Testing.Platform without this workaround.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the equivalent flags for Microsoft.Testing.Platform—things like `--filter` for test filtering, `--report-trx` for TRX logging (with the appropriate extension), `--collect-coverage` for code coverage, and specialized flags like `--crashdump` and `--hangdump` for diagnostic data. Each of these requires specific NuGet packages to function. For .NET 8 specifically, since native MTP support isn't available through `dotnet test`, you'd need to either invoke the test executable directly or use `dotnet run` to pass arguments to the testing platform.\n\nThe practical solution for .NET 8 is to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` package, which bridges the gap and lets you continue using `dotnet test` while passing MTP-specific arguments after the `--` separator. This way you can combine standard test filters with the platform's advanced diagnostics and reporting options in a single command. I need to clarify how the MTP runner integrates with `dotnet test` through MSBuild, since the arguments get passed through after the `--` separator.","outputTokens":1499,"requestId":"680D:13E67C:78099D:7F7E63:6A044DA8"},"id":"e69cc04f-5f1c-4022-a95a-e648e088c215","timestamp":"2026-05-